{ This study is designed to let you play "solitaire chess" with the best games of Paul Morphy. You'll play alongside Morphy, trying to guess his moves.

The opening moves are indicated by arrows. Just play those out. After the first few moves, the exercise starts. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 { The King's Gambit. Modern engines don't love it, but it's an opening with a rich tradition that can still be effective in games between humans. } 2... exf4 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Qh4+ { [%cal Ge1f1] } 4. Kf1 { The king is forced to move, but it's (reasonably) safe on f1, and Black will have to lose time retreating the queen at some point. } 4... Bc5 { Start here! You're playing as White alongside Morphy. } 5. d4! { Preventing Black's threat of Qf2# while grabbing space in the center and hitting the bishop. } 5... Bb6 6. Nf3 { Developing while also creating a threat is almost always a good idea. } 6... Qe7 7. Nc3 { The other knight enters the game, while defending e4 and perhaps threatening to jump into d5. } 7... Nf6 8. Qd3 { Defending the pawn on e4. The advance e5, driving away Black's knight, would have been even stronger. } (8. e5 { Also a good move, in fact stronger than what Morphy played. Give him a break, he was only 11. }) 8... c6 9. Bxf4 { Taking a pawn and bringing out the last minor piece. } 9... d5 10. exd5 { No reason not to take. } 10... O-O 11. d6 { An advanced passed pawn can be very dangerous. This move also opens the diagonal for the bishop on c4 and gains a tempo on Black's queen. } (11. Re1 { is also a very good choice. }) 11... Qd8 12. Re1 { Bringing another piece into the game. } 12... Re8 13. Ng5 { Taking advantage of the downside of Black's last move: it weakened the defense of f7. } 13... Rxe1+ 14. Kxe1 Qe8+ 15. Kd2 { Surrounded by White's pieces, the king is safe here. } (15. Kf1 { is not as good because it locks the rook in on h1. }) 15... Be6 16. Re1 { What really set Morphy apart was that he used EVERY piece. The rook joins the party, increasing the pressure on the bishop on e6 and pinning it to the queen. } 16... Nbd7 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rxe6 { Here Black resigned because there is no good defense to the threat of taking the queen, or other discovered checks by moving the rook. } (18. Bxe6+ Kh8 { is not quite as crushing, although of course White is still doing very well. } 19. Bb3 { [%cal Ge1e8] } (19. Bxd7 Qxd7 20. Re7) 19... Qf8) 18... Qf7 (18... Qd8 19. Re8# { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge8g8] } (19. Rxf6+)) 19. Re7 { [%cal Gc4g8] } 1-0


