{ This is Morphy's most famous game, so if you've already seen it before, you can skip it. But if not, you're in for a treat.

The game was played in an opera house in Paris. Morphy took on a team of two opponents in consultation. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 d6 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 3. d4 Bg4 { Start here! } 4. dxe5 Bxf3 { How could you have a won a pawn if Black played dxe5? } 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 { Developing a piece and threatening mate. } 6... Nf6 7. Qb3 { "Never move a piece twice in the opening, unless there's a tactic." Here the tactic is a double attack on f7 and b7. The absence of Black's light-squared bishop makes this hard to deal with. } 7... Qe7 8. Nc3 { Morphy prioritizes development over grabbing a pawn. } (8. Qxb7 { Grabbing the pawn would allow Black to force a queen trade with Qb4+. Being up a pawn in the endgame is also a good outcome, so this move is not bad at all, but apparently Morphy wanted to finish things in the middlegame. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. c3) (8. Bxf7+ { Another good option. If Black takes, they will no longer have the resource of Qb4+. } 8... Qxf7 9. Qxb7 { [%csl Ra8][%cal Gb7a8] }) 8... c6 9. Bg5 { Pinning the knight. } 9... b5 10. Nxb5! { Very important move! If you wanted to retreat the bishop, pay special attention to this one. You have a huge lead in development! Why should your opponent get to push you around? } 10... cxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. O-O-O! { The most efficient way to get the rooks into the game. } (12. Rd1 { Not as good as 0-0-0 because the h1 rook cannot now go to the d-file. }) 12... Rd8 13. Rxd7! { Keeping the momentum going. } (13. Rd3 { Not as stylish as Morphy's move, but equally effective. }) 13... Rxd7 14. Rd1 { All pieces in the game! } 14... Qe6 15. Bxd7+ { Normally you would not want to let your opponent out of a pin like this, but Morphy has already seen a game-ending combination. } 15... Nxd7 16. Qb8+! { Bam! } 16... Nxb8 17. Rd8# { And it's mate on the board. One of the great chess games of all time. } 1-0


