[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. e4 { In this game Morphy had Black. Play out the opening moves. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 { [%cal Gf8c5] } 3... Bc5 4. b4 { The Evans Gambit. In exchange for the pawn, White gains time to expand in the center. Not a bad opening at all, even today! } { [%cal Gc5b4] } 4... Bxb4 5. c3 { [%cal Gb4a5] } 5... Ba5 6. d4 { [%cal Ge5d4] } 6... exd4 7. e5 { Start here! } 7... d5! { Fighting back in the center and preparing to develop the bishop. } 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O Nge7 { Developing a knight and preparing to castle, while blocking a potential check on the e-file. } 10. Ng5 O-O { Castling and defending f7 at the same time. } 11. Bd3 Bf5 { Once again answering White's threat with a developing move. } 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Ba3 Qg6 { White wins an exchange, but in the meantime Morphy has developed all his pieces and grabbed some pawns. } 14. Bxf8 Qxg5 { The right piece to take. The knight was one of the White king's only defenders, whereas the bishop doesn't have much to do. } 15. Ba3 dxc3 { Development is great, but there's also nothing wrong with grabbing a free pawn. } 16. Bc1 Qg6 17. Bf4 Rd8 { Last piece in the game! Have you noticed how Morphy manages to involve EVERY piece in EVERY game? } 18. Qc2 Ncd4 { The knight jumps into the center of the board while attacking the queen. } 19. Qe4 Ng3!! { A sudden end to the game! Morphy threatens both checkmate and capturing the queen. White can't stop both. } 20. Qxg6 Nde2# 0-1


