{ You're playing as Black alongside Morphy. Play out the opening moves. }
1. e4 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 { [%cal Gf8c5] } 4... Bc5 5. O-O { [%cal Ge8g8] } 5... O-O 6. Nxe5 { [%cal Gf8e8] } 6... Re8 { Morphy sacrifices a pawn for quick development. } 7. Nxc6 { [%cal Gd7c6] } 7... dxc6 8. Bc4 { Start here! } 8... b5 { Making the bishop choose a diagonal. } (8... Ng4 { with the idea of Qh4 would in fact have been stronger than Morphy's move. }) (8... Nxe4 { fails to a tactic. } 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. Qf3+ { [%cal Gf3f7,Gf3e4] }) 9. Be2 Nxe4 { Now it is safe to take the pawn. } 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. Bf3 Re6 { Keeping c6 defended. } 12. c3 Qd3! { A very important move: White can't be allowed to play d4 and take command of the center. } 13. b4 Bb6 (13... Bd6 { also a good option. }) 14. a4 bxa4 { Accepting doubled isolated pawns, but White was threatening to trap the bishop with a5. And if you checkmate your opponent nobody will care about the isolated pawns! } 15. Qxa4 Bd7 (15... Bb7 { would have been stronger, preventing the defensive idea Qa6. }) 16. Ra2 Rae8 { Last piece in the game! } 17. Qa6 Qxf3!! { This queen sacrifice blows White's king position wide open. } 18. gxf3 Rg6+ 19. Kh1 Bh3 { Threatening to set up a checkmate starting with Bg2. } 20. Rd1 Bg2+ 21. Kg1 Bxf3+ 22. Kf1 Bg2+ { Morphy decides to repeat moves. } (22... Rg2 { was the fastest win, planning Rxh2 and Rh1#. }) 23. Kg1 Bh3+ 24. Kh1 Bxf2 { Threatening Bg2#. } 25. Qf1 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 { White has made it into the endgame without getting checkmated, but he's down 2 pawns, and the king isn't out of the woods yet. } 26... Re2 { Rooks on the seventh are usually powerful, and this is no exception. } 27. Ra1 Rh6 { Preparing to break through on h2. } 28. d4 Be3! { Blocking the threat to the rook on h6 while adding another attacker to h2. White resigned in view of the line Bxe3 Rhxh2+ Kg1 Reg2#. } 0-1


