{ This game was played against Ernest Morphy, Paul's Uncle.

Start by playing out the opening moves. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { The Evans Gambit. We've already seen this with Morphy playing Black in a previous game. } { [%cal Gb2b4] } 4. b4 Bxb4 { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 Ba5 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 6. d4 exd4 { [%cal Ge1g1] } 7. O-O Bxc3 { Start here! } 8. Nxc3 { Eliminating the bishop, one of Black's only developed pieces. } 8... dxc3 9. Ba3 { White had many good choices here. Morphy develops a bishop and makes it harder for Black to castle. } (9. Qb3 { Good move, pressuring f7. }) (9. Qd5 { Not bad, but Black can defend f7 with the queen, and then White will likely have to move the queen again when it gets attacked on d5. }) 9... d6 10. Qb3 { Attacking f7 and getting ready to regain the pawn on c3. } 10... Nh6 11. Qxc3 { This is a good time to pocket the pawn, also threatening g7. } 11... Qf6 12. e5! { Key move! Still down a pawn, and with Black's king in the center, White doesn't want a queen trade. } (12. Qxf6? { This doubles Black's pawns, but Black will still be up a pawn in the endgame, and with queens off the board it will be much harder to create an attack. }) 12... dxe5 13. Rfe1 { Bringing another piece into the game and eyeing Black's king. } (13. Bd5 { Also good, pressuring the knight. }) (13. Bb5 { Also good, pressuring the knight. }) 13... Bd7 14. Rab1 { The last piece enters the game while creating another threat, this time the pawn on b7. } 14... O-O-O 15. Ba6! { Wasting no time ripping Black's king position open, even at the cost of a piece. } (15. Qb3 { allows b6 and it's hard to make further progress on the queenside. }) 15... Na5 { If bxa6 Morphy would have played Qb3, and Black's king will be flushed out. } 16. Rec1! { threatening checkmate on c7. } (16. Qxa5? { would be met by Qxa6 and White has no good way to continue the attack. }) 16... Bc6 17. Qxa5 { Now that the bishop has been forced to c6 this is much stronger. } 17... bxa6 18. Qxa6+ (18. Nxe5 { is also winning. }) 18... Kd7 19. Rxc6! { Setting up a little combination. } 19... Qf5 { Qxc6 would have allowed Nxe5+. The rest of the game is a mop-up operation. } 20. Rxc7+ { White had many good moves, but this leads to a quick checkmate. } 20... Ke8 { If Kxc7 then Qb7#. } 21. Qc6+ Qd7 22. Rb8 { Morphy decides to finish the game with a flashy mate. } (22. Rxd7 { also wins of course. }) 22... Qxc6 23. Re7+ Kf8 24. Rxd8+ Qe8 25. Rdxe8# { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


